canonical:
  title: 靈神菴
  author: 金宗直
  language: lzh
  text: 箭筈車箱散策回老禪方丈石門開明朝更踏紅塵路須喚山都沽酒來
  rtl: true
  vertical: true
lzh_formatted:
  title: 靈神菴
  author: 金宗直
  language: lzh
  text: 箭筈車箱散策回。老禪方丈石門開。明朝更踏紅塵路。須喚山都沽酒來。
korean:
  title: 영신암
  author: 김종직
  language: kor
  text: |-
    전괄과 거상으로 산책하다 돌아오니
    방장의 늙은 중은 돌문을 열어 준다
    내일 아침에는 다시 홍진의 길을 밟으리니
    모름지기 산도를 불러 술을 사오게 하라
  url: https://db.itkc.or.kr/dir/item?itemId=BT#dir/node?dataId=ITKC_BT_1365A_1450_020_0510&viewSync=OT
  footnotes:
  - key: '[주-D001] 전괄(箭筈) : '
    value: 화살의 머리로서 활줄이 닿는 곳을 말하는데, 여기서 한 말은 미상이다.
  - key: '[주-D002] 산도(山都) : '
    value: 유인원(類人猿)의 일종이다.
english:
  title: The Spirit Hermitage
  author: Kim Jong-jik
  language: eng
  text: |-
    I return from wandering through the valleys,
    the arrow-notches and cart-wheels scattered behind.
    The old abbot opens the stone gate of his cell.
    Tomorrow I'll walk again on the dusty roads of the world.
    So summon the mountain ape to bring us wine.
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: The 'arrow-notches and cart-wheels' likely refer to the Buddhist pilgrim's journey through natural landscape, though their precise symbolic meaning remains elusive.
  - key: ''
    value: The 'mountain ape' (山都) is a playful reference to a legendary creature, used here perhaps as a metaphor for the untamed spirit of nature that brings wine—suggesting the poet's ironic acceptance of returning to worldly life.
